v141: The Pareto-Lorenz a coefficients were computed using the top shares estimates. As a rule they were estimated from the top 0.1% share within the top 1% share: a=1/[1-log(S1%/S0.1%)/log(10)]. When the top 0.1% and top 1% shares were not available, the closest substitutes were used. Series based on shares excluding capital gains up to 1919, and including capital gains from 1925.
v142: The inverted Pareto-Lorenz b coefficients were computed from the Pareto-Lorenz coefficients using the formula b=a/(a-1). Alternatively they can be computed by using directly the top income shares series and the formula: b=1/[log(S1%/S0.1%)/log(10)]. Series based on shares excluding capital gains up to 1919, and including capital gains from 1925.
v155: There is a break in the official series in 2011. From 2012 to 2014 we assume a linearly rising population (consistent with post 2011 census data). To be updated when homogenous official series are published. Population does seem to be rising since 2011 (with +700K foreigners from 2011 to 2013).
